==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|beholden}}, from {{inh|en|ang|behealdan||to hold, have, occupy, possess, guard, preserve, contain, belong, keep, observe, consider, behold, look at, gaze on, see, signify, avail, effect, take care, beware, be cautious, restrain, act, behave}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*bihaldaną||to hold with, keep}}, equivalent to {{prefix|be|hold|lang=en}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|behouden||to keep, restrain, preserve}}, {{cog|de|behalten||to keep, restrain, remember}}, {{etyl|da|-}} and {{cog|no|beholde||to keep}} and {{cog|sv|behålla||to keep}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/bɪˈhəʊld/|lang=en}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|/bɪˈhoʊld/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-behold.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|beholds|beholding|beheld|beheld|past_ptc2=beholden|past_ptc2_qual=rare}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[see]], or to [[look at]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1898|author={{w|Winston Churchill (novelist)|Winston Churchill}}
|title={{w|The Celebrity}}|chapter=8
|passage=The humor of my proposition appealed more strongly to Miss Trevor than I had looked for, and from that time forward she became her old self again;{{...}}. Now she had come to look upon the matter in its true proportions, and her anticipation of a possible chance of teaching him a lesson was a pleasure to '''behold'''.}}

====Usage notes====
Rarely used in informal speech. The past participle [[beholden]] now has a meaning detached from the other forms of the word.

